Here are the command lines and explanations to accomplish those file-searching and manipulation tasks.
Searching and Counting Directories

    How many sub-directories does it have? Use find and pipe to wc.
    find . -type d | wc -l

    Why will the human remove one from the count?
    The find . command includes the current directory (.) in its output. Subtracting one gives you the true count of the sub-directories inside it.

Listing and Finding Specific Files

    List all files called act1.html one level down from this directory.
    ls */act1.html

    Find Act 3 of Macbeth and show its size.
    To find it and show the size in a detailed list format:
    ls -l Macbeth/act3.html
    (If you aren't sure of the exact folder name, you could use ls -l */act3.html | grep -i macbeth)

    List all "Act 6" files in all plays.
    ls */act6.html
    (This will likely return an error like "No such file or directory," since Shakespeare's plays only go up to 5 acts).

    Write a command to check if any "Act 7" files exist.
    ls */act7.html

    From your home directory, list all the "Act 6" files without changing directory.
    Assuming your Shakespeare directory is in your home folder:
    ls ~/Shakespeare/*/act6.html

Using grep to Search Inside Files

    Use grep to find all lines where "Ireland" appears in the plays (only in complete.html).
    grep "Ireland" */complete.html

    In how many lines of the plays does "Ireland" appear? Use grep and wc.
    grep "Ireland" */complete.html | wc -l

    In how many different plays does "Ireland" appear? Use grep with a certain option.
    grep -l "Ireland" */complete.html | wc -l
    (The -l option tells grep to only output the names of the files that contain a match, rather than the matching lines themselves. Counting those files gives you the number of plays).

    Show all lines that contain "Scot" but not "Scots", "Scotland", or "Scottish".
    grep "Scot" */complete.html | grep -v "Scots" | grep -v "Scotland" | grep -v "Scottish"
    (The -v option stands for "invert match"—it filters out lines containing those specific strings).

    How many times does the string "Scotland" appear in Act 3 of a Shakespeare play?
    grep -o "Scotland" */act3.html | wc -l
    (Using the -o option is important here. Standard grep outputs the whole line. If "Scotland" appears twice on the same line, grep | wc -l would only count it once. -o puts every exact match on its own line, giving you a true count).

Search Engine vs. Command Line

    How would you find the answer to the previous using Google or other search engine?
    You would use site-specific operators combined with exact phrase matching on a dedicated Shakespeare text site. For example: "Scotland" "Act 3" site:shakespeare.mit.edu. However, standard search engines are poor at cross-referencing specific structural file locations (like */act3.html). To get an exact count easily, you would need to use a specialized database like Open Source Shakespeare, which allows parameter-based text searches.

    List all the plays in which the word "idiot" occurs.
    grep -l "idiot" */complete.html

    List all the plays in which the word "idiot" does not occur.
    grep -L "idiot" */complete.html
    (The capital -L option does the exact opposite of -l; it lists files that do not contain the match).

Web Server Test Suite Task

    Go to the test suite and list all web pages (HTML files) one level down.
    Bash

    cd /users/tutors/mhumphrysdculab/share/testsuite
    ls */*.html

    How do you search for the string "http://computing.dcu.ie/~humphrys/" in all the web pages?
    grep -F "[http://computing.dcu.ie/~humphrys/](http://computing.dcu.ie/~humphrys/)" */*.html
    (Using -F tells grep to treat the string as fixed, literal text rather than a regular expression, which prevents special characters like . and ~ from causing unexpected behavior).

    How would you find that string in all the web pages using a Web browser? Or using a text editor?

        Web Browser: You generally cannot do this efficiently across an entire server via a browser. You would have to load every individual page, view the page source (Ctrl+U), and use the browser's "Find" feature (Ctrl+F).

        Text Editor: Modern text editors (like VS Code, Notepad++, or Sublime Text) have a "Find in Files" feature (usually Ctrl+Shift+F). You select the parent folder, input the string, and the editor will search the contents of every file in that directory structure.

File and Directory Size

    List the "testsuite" directories sorted by size. (Use du and sort).
    du -sk * | sort -n
    (This gets the disk usage in Kilobytes (-k) for each item, without showing subdirectories (-s), and sorts them numerically (-n)).

    List the "act" files in Shakespeare sorted by size. (Use ls or du, along with sort).
    du -sk */act*.html | sort -n
    (Alternatively, you can just use ls directly: ls -S */act*.html sorts by file size largest to smallest).
